deck: American publisher of the mid 19th century
description:
The company went through several names before being named A.C. McClurg & Co. Founded in Chicago in 1844 it was first known as S.C. Griggs & Co and from 1848 it was known as Griggs, Bross & Co. for eighteen months when William Bross joined the company as a partner. Then when Alexander Caldwell McClurg joined the company in 1859 and climbed the company ladder. The company was renamed again, to Jansen, McClurg & Co., in 1871 when Griggs sold his share of the company after the great Chicago fire destroyed the building. Then finally the name became A.C. McClurg & Co. after Alexander Caldwell McClurg became senior partner.

Unfortunately the company burned down again in 1899. McClurg reorganized as a company that sold shares to it's employees. McClurg died in 1901 after financing a new building and the company didn't turn out too many publications until 1914 when they published Tarzan of the Apes, which was a best seller. They published ten more Tarzan books until Burroughs set up his own publishing house for his big selling and by then very famous character.

The company chose to close down it's only bookstore in Chicago to focus it's efforts on the wholesale business in 1923. In 1962 the company went belly-up still calling itself A.C. McClurg & Co.
name: A.C. McClurg & Co.

deck: A comic publishing company founded in 2012.
description:
Black Mask Studios is an American comic book and graphic novel publishing company founded by filmmaker Matt Pizzolo (Godkiller, Halo-8), Steve Niles (30 Days of Night, Simon Dark), and Brett Gurewitz (Bad Religion, CEO of Epitaph Records) in 2012, with "the aim of disrupting the comics market".

Published Titles in 2013

  • 12 Reasons To Die
    Wu-Tang Clan’s RZA & Ghostface Killah collaborated with Adrian Younge, writers Matthew Rosenberg & Patrick Kindlon, and a rotating roster of artists including Riley Rossmo and Tim Seeley on this wild horror-gangster hybrid story that spans from comics to music.

  • Occupy Comics
    The eagerly anticipated Occupy Comics anthology, a unique time capsule & forum for stories inspired by Occupy Wall Street. All profits will be donated to various Occupy-related actions. A Kickstarter Funded project.

  • Liberator
    A hard-edged vigilante series about two young heroes who avenge the torture of animals. Created by real-life animal rescuer Matt Miner.
  • Ballistic
    The madcap, transreal, new sci-fi adventure by Darick Robertson (Transmetropolitan, The Boys, Happy!) and Adam Egypt Mortimer (director of Grant Morrison’s upcoming Sinatoro).

A second slate of titles began debuting in Fall 2014 and continue to launch

Space Riders written by Fabian Rangel Jr., illustrate by Alexis Ziritt

Young Terrorists written by Matt Pizzolo, illustrated by Amancay Nahuelpan

The Disciples written by Steve Niles, illustrated by Christopher Mitten

Mayday written by Curt Pires, illustrated by Chris Peterson

Toe Tag Riot written by Matt Miner, illustrated by Sean Von Gorman (October 2014 - April 2015)

We Can Never Go Home written by Matthew Rosenberg and Patrick Kindlon, illustrated by Josh Hood

Transference written by Michael Moreci, illustrated by Ron Salas

Godkiller written by Matt Pizzolo, illustrated by Anna Muckcracker Wieszczyk, covers by Ben Templesmith

Critical Hit written by Matt Miner, illustrated by Jonathan Brandon Sawyer. A sequel to Liberator.

Pirouette written by Mark Miller, illustrated by Carlos Granda

Last Born written by Patrick Meaney, illustrated by Eric Zawadzki (October 2014 - December 2014)
name: Black Mask Studios
